{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473480"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:09:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:09:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2464"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2464"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.05,0.33,0.6,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67164"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1058"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38945"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department via ambulance with sudden onset hoarse voice and urticarial rash immediately following a bee sting. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min and blood pressure 85/50 mmHg. Intravenous access has been obtained.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following blood tests is most likely to support the diagnosis of anaphylaxis if performed within two hours of symptom onset?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood cultures","Complement C3a, C4a and C5a levels","Specific immunoglobulin E antibodies","Serum tryptase","C1 esterase inhibitor level"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of anaphylaxis including acute onset urticaria, upper airway involvement (hoarse voice), and hypotension following a clear trigger. While the diagnosis is primarily clinical, laboratory tests can provide supportive evidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum tryptase\u003C/strong\u003E is the most useful laboratory test to confirm anaphylaxis. Levels begin to rise within minutes of mast cell degranulation, peak at 1-2 hours, and remain elevated for up to 24 hours. Serial measurements (at presentation, 1-2 hours, and 24 hours) can demonstrate a rise and fall pattern characteristic of anaphylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are used to identify bacteraemia in sepsis. While septic shock can present with hypotension and tachycardia, the rapid onset, clear trigger (bee sting), and presence of urticaria make this diagnosis unlikely. Additionally, blood cultures take 24-48 hours for results, making them unhelpful for immediate diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement C3a, C4a and C5a levels\u003C/strong\u003E are components of the complement cascade that may be activated during anaphylaxis. However, these tests are primarily research tools, are not widely available, and results are not available quickly enough to aid in acute diagnosis. Furthermore, complement activation occurs in many inflammatory conditions, making these tests non-specific.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecific immunoglobulin E antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E measure allergic sensitisation to specific allergens. While useful in the outpatient setting for identifying triggers and planning future management, these levels do not change acutely during anaphylaxis. Results typically take days to return and therefore cannot assist with immediate diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC1 esterase inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E testing is used to diagnose hereditary angioedema, a rare genetic condition causing episodes of swelling. Unlike anaphylaxis, hereditary angioedema episodes develop over hours to days, do not cause urticaria or hypotension, and are not triggered by allergens. The test is neither sensitive nor specific for anaphylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Serum tryptase peaks 1-2 hours after anaphylaxis onset and remains elevated for up to 24 hours.","Tryptase measurement should not delay emergency management of anaphylaxis.","Clinical diagnosis of anaphylaxis is based on rapid onset of multiple system involvement following exposure to a likely trigger."],"references":["Schwartz LB. Diagnostic value of tryptase in anaphylaxis and mastocytosis. Immunol Allergy Clin North Am. 2006;26(3):451-463. doi:10.1016/j.iac.2006.05.010","National Clinical Guideline Centre (UK). Drug Allergy: Diagnosis and Management of Drug Allergy in Adults, Children and Young People. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (UK); 2014 Sep. (NICE Clinical Guidelines, No. 183.) 7, Measuring serum tryptase after suspected anaphylaxis. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK274147/","ASCIA contributors, 2020. Laboratory investigation of allergic diseases (Internet). Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy. Access at: https://www.allergy.org.au/hp//papers/tests-in-the-diagnosis-of-allergic-diseases.","https://www.uptodate.com/contents/laboratory-tests-to-support-the-clinical-diagnosis-of-anaphylaxis?search=serum%20igE%20testing\u0026topicRef=5540\u0026source=see_link"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67164"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2464"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67164"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T11:38:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T11:40:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position"